%==============================================================================
\chapter{System Overview}
\label{ch:overview}
%==============================================================================

\section{What Pragya Is}
Pragya (प्रज्ञा, Sanskrit for \emph{wisdom}) is an \textbf{Enterprise RAG Knowledge Platform}:
a web application that lets the employees of an organization query their internal documents in
natural language and receive grounded, cited answers. Architecturally it is two cooperating
systems:

\begin{itemize}
  \item A \textbf{Python/FastAPI backend} handling authentication, document ingestion, vector
  search, answer generation, and analytics. It is fully asynchronous, organized into a strict
  three-layer structure (routing $\rightarrow$ services $\rightarrow$ data), and backed by a
  cloud PostgreSQL database (Neon) for relational data and a Qdrant vector database for
  semantic search.
  \item A \textbf{Next.js 15 frontend} providing the chat interface, document management,
  conversation history, the meeting assistant, and the admin dashboard. It never touches a
  database directly; it communicates only through the backend's HTTP API.
\end{itemize}

The system was built as a six-week internship project at HCL Infosystems, following a
deliberate module-by-module build order (foundation $\rightarrow$ auth $\rightarrow$ ingestion
$\rightarrow$ RAG chat $\rightarrow$ document intelligence $\rightarrow$ conversation history
$\rightarrow$ analytics $\rightarrow$ meeting assistant), each module tested and committed
before the next began.

\section{The Problem It Solves}
Organizational knowledge has three chronic failure modes that Pragya addresses simultaneously:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Knowledge is locked in documents nobody fully reads.} Policies and handbooks
  are long; the answer to a specific question is one sentence buried on page 14.
  \item \textbf{Generic AI assistants are confidently wrong about company specifics} and cannot
  cite a source---the \emph{hallucination} problem.
  \item \textbf{Sensitive documents must not leak across departments.} Finance, Legal, and HR
  hold material other departments should not see.
\end{enumerate}

Pragya grounds answers in the actual corpus (addressing 1 and 2), enforces the hallucination
guard at the prompt level while surfacing citations for verification (2), and enforces
per-department access control at the vector-database query layer so the rule cannot be bypassed
by application logic (3).

\section{Users \& Roles}
Pragya recognizes three roles, stored on \code{users.role} and carried in every JWT. The role is
a plain string (not a database enum) so new roles need no schema migration.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{User roles and their capabilities.}
\label{tab:roles}
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{l L{3.2cm} X}
\toprule
\textbf{Role} & \textbf{Who} & \textbf{Capabilities}\\
\midrule
\code{admin} & Department / org administrators & Everything a user can, plus: manage departments,
change user roles, upload \emph{company-wide} documents, access any department's
department-level documents, and view analytics. The first user to register is auto-promoted to
\code{admin}.\\
\code{user} & Regular employees & Ask questions, upload documents (own department or personal),
document intelligence, meeting assistant, document search, own conversation history.\\
\code{viewer} & Read-oriented accounts & A lighter role; gated like \code{user} for queries.\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

Every user belongs to at most one department (\code{users.department\_id}, nullable). The
department is the backbone of access control: it determines which documents a user's queries
can reach. A user with no department cannot query documents at all, and the chat endpoint
rejects such a request.

\section{The Three Defining Features}
\begin{description}
  \item[Hybrid retrieval (dense + sparse).] Dense semantic retrieval is excellent at meaning
  but blind to exact tokens; an abbreviation like ``CL'' (casual leave) has no useful embedding
  neighborhood. Pragya runs dense and sparse keyword retrieval in parallel and fuses them with
  Reciprocal Rank Fusion (Chapter~\ref{ch:retrieval}).
  \item[Citation grounding.] The model answers only from provided context, cites every claim as
  \code{[Source: N]}, and returns a fixed refusal if the answer is absent. Citations are
  enforceable and checkable (Chapter~\ref{ch:generation}).
  \item[Vector-layer access control.] A visibility filter is built into every Qdrant query, so a
  forbidden document is never a candidate---access control is not an afterthought applied to
  results (Chapter~\ref{ch:generation}).
\end{description}

\section{Technology Stack \& Justification}
\label{sec:stack}
Every choice was made deliberately and recorded in configuration rather than hardcoded.
Table~\ref{tab:stack} summarizes the stack (versions from \code{requirements.txt} and
\code{package.json}); the prose justifies the non-obvious choices.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{The Pragya technology stack.}
\label{tab:stack}
\small
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{L{2.6cm} L{4.2cm} X}
\toprule
\textbf{Layer} & \textbf{Choice (version)} & \textbf{Why}\\
\midrule
API framework & FastAPI (async) \code{\textasciitilde0.115} & Native async, automatic OpenAPI \code{/docs}, Pydantic validation.\\
Runtime & Python 3.11 & Mature AI/ML ecosystem; async maturity.\\
ASGI server & Uvicorn \code{[standard]} \code{\textasciitilde0.34} & uvloop + httptools for speed.\\
ORM & SQLAlchemy \code{[asyncio]} \code{\textasciitilde2.0} & Async ORM; logic in Python.\\
Migrations & Alembic \code{\textasciitilde1.14} & Autogenerated from models.\\
Relational DB & Neon (serverless PostgreSQL) & Managed Postgres, scales to zero, SSL-required.\\
Driver & asyncpg \code{\textasciitilde0.30} & Fast async Postgres driver.\\
Vector DB & Qdrant (client \code{\textasciitilde1.12}) & Native hybrid search: named dense + sparse vectors.\\
Embeddings & Gemini \code{gemini-embedding-001} @ 768d & Matryoshka truncation 3072$\to$768.\\
Chat LLM & Gemini Flash (from config) & Fast, free-tier-friendly; model string in \code{.env}.\\
Reranker & \code{ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2} & Joint query-document scoring; local ($\sim$85\,MB).\\
PDF parsing & PyMuPDF (\code{fitz}) \code{\textasciitilde1.25} & Keeps page numbers (citations need them).\\
DOCX / PPTX & python-docx / python-pptx & Native Office parsing.\\
Auth & python-jose + passlib(bcrypt) & Email + password only; bcrypt pinned \code{4.0.1}.\\
Config & pydantic-settings \code{\textasciitilde2.7} & Typed settings from \code{.env}.\\
Frontend & Next.js 15 + React 19 & Server components, file routing.\\
Styling & Tailwind CSS v4 & Token-driven utility CSS.\\
Client cache & SWR \code{\textasciicircum2.4} & Cache-first reads, background revalidation.\\
Charts & Recharts \code{\textasciicircum3.8} & Analytics dashboard visualizations.\\
Evaluation & RAGAS \code{0.2.0} & RAG metrics (faithfulness, context precision).\\
Judges & Groq \code{llama-3.1-8b-instant} + Ollama \code{qwen2.5:7b} & Independent of the generator.\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Why FastAPI + async everywhere.} RAG is I/O-bound: one question waits on embedding
calls, vector search, the relational DB, and a streaming LLM response. An async framework
serves other requests during those waits instead of blocking a thread each. FastAPI's automatic
\code{/docs} made every module testable the moment it was built.

\paragraph{Why Qdrant specifically.} The defining feature is \emph{hybrid} retrieval, and Qdrant
supports \textbf{named vectors}: a single collection holds a dense \emph{and} a sparse vector per
point, queried by name. Hybrid retrieval is thus a first-class capability of the store. Qdrant
also supports indexed payload filtering---exactly what the department/visibility access control
needs.

\paragraph{Why Gemini embeddings at 768 dimensions.} \code{gemini-embedding-001} natively produces
3072-dimensional vectors. Pragya truncates them to 768 using \emph{Matryoshka} representation (a
prefix of the vector is itself a valid embedding), giving a smaller, faster index at negligible
quality cost. Cosine distance is scale-invariant, so no re-normalization is needed.

\paragraph{Why a cross-encoder reranker.} Dense and sparse retrieval are \emph{bi-encoders}---query
and document embedded independently. A \emph{cross-encoder} feeds the pair through a transformer
together, relating every query token to every document token---far more accurate but costlier, so
it runs only on the $\sim$40 fused candidates. Whether it \emph{helps} on this corpus is an
empirical question the evaluation answers (Chapter~\ref{ch:eval}).

\begin{divergence}
\code{CLAUDE.md} specifies ``Gemini Flash --- model string from config'' and does not hardcode a
model. The committed evaluation results record the generator used for the benchmark as
\code{gemini-3.1-flash-lite}. This report uses that real recorded value wherever a concrete model
name is needed, and treats the configurable \code{GEMINI\_CHAT\_MODEL} as the source of truth in
the running system.
\end{divergence}

\section{Top-Level System Architecture}
At the highest level Pragya is a browser client talking to a FastAPI backend, which orchestrates
three external systems---Neon PostgreSQL (relational data), Qdrant (vector search with access
filtering), and Gemini (embeddings and chat)---plus a local cross-encoder for reranking
(Figure~\ref{fig:arch}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=7mm and 14mm]
% Client
\node[accentbox, minimum width=46mm] (ui) {Browser --- Next.js 15 frontend\\\footnotesize Chat $\cdot$ Documents $\cdot$ Conversations\\\footnotesize Meeting $\cdot$ Admin $\cdot$ Analytics};
% Backend layers
\node[box, below=12mm of ui, minimum width=30mm] (router) {\code{routers/}\\\scriptsize HTTP only};
\node[box, below=of router, minimum width=30mm] (svc) {\code{services/}\\\scriptsize business logic};
\node[box, below=of svc, minimum width=30mm] (model) {\code{models/}\\\scriptsize ORM / data access};
\node[box, right=20mm of router, minimum width=26mm] (rbac) {\code{middleware/rbac}\\\scriptsize JWT + role gates};
% External
\node[db, below left=14mm and 2mm of model] (pg) {Neon\\PostgreSQL};
\node[db, below=16mm of model] (qd) {Qdrant\\dense+sparse};
\node[box, below right=14mm and 2mm of model, minimum width=24mm] (gem) {Gemini APIs\\\scriptsize embed + chat (SSE)};
\node[box, right=14mm of svc, minimum width=26mm] (rr) {Cross-encoder\\\scriptsize reranker (in-proc)};
% Edges
\draw[arr] (ui) -- node[lbl,right]{HTTPS/JSON, Bearer JWT} (router);
\draw[darr] (router) -- node[lbl,left]{SSE stream} (ui);
\draw[arr] (router) -- (svc);
\draw[arr] (svc) -- (model);
\draw[darr] (router) -- (rbac);
\draw[arr] (model) -- (pg);
\draw[arr] (svc) to[bend left=8] node[lbl,right]{RBAC-filtered search} (qd);
\draw[arr] (svc.south) to[bend right=12] (gem.north);
\draw[arr] (svc) -- (rr);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Top-level system architecture: client $\rightarrow$ three-layer backend $\rightarrow$
Neon / Qdrant / Gemini, with the RBAC middleware gating requests and a local reranker.}
\label{fig:arch}
\end{figure}

A request enters through a router (HTTP only: validate, authenticate via the RBAC middleware,
call a service, return). Services hold all logic; the data layer is the only thing touching
PostgreSQL. Vector search, embedding, generation, and reranking are service-layer concerns
reaching out to Qdrant, Gemini, and the local reranker. The rule that the access filter lives
\emph{inside} the Qdrant query is the structural backbone the rest of this report details.

%==============================================================================
\chapter{Data Model \& Ingestion Pipeline}
\label{ch:data}
%==============================================================================

This chapter describes how Pragya stores knowledge---both relational records in PostgreSQL
and vectors in Qdrant---and how a raw uploaded file becomes searchable knowledge.

\section{Schema Conventions}
All relational data lives in Neon PostgreSQL, modeled with SQLAlchemy's async ORM in
\code{backend/models/}. Three conventions are enforced project-wide:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{UUID primary keys}, generated application-side via \code{uuid.uuid4}. IDs never
  depend on a DB sequence and are unguessable.
  \item \textbf{Timezone-aware timestamps} (\code{TIMESTAMPTZ}). A shared \code{\_utcnow()} returns
  \code{datetime.now(timezone.utc)}. (An early build used naive timestamps; a migration converted
  all of them---see Chapter~\ref{ch:journey}.)
  \item \textbf{Status / role fields are plain strings, not enums}, so new states
  (\code{processing}/\code{ready}/\code{failed}) or roles need no migration.
\end{itemize}

\section{The Seven Tables}
The seven tables divide into three groups: identity \& access (\code{departments},
\code{users}), knowledge (\code{documents}, \code{document\_chunks}), and conversation \&
analytics (\code{chat\_sessions}, \code{chat\_messages}, \code{query\_logs}).
Table~\ref{tab:schema} lists every column of every table.

\begin{small}
\begin{longtable}{L{3.1cm} L{2.4cm} L{2.8cm} X}
\caption{Complete relational schema (all seven tables, every column).}
\label{tab:schema}\\
\toprule
\textbf{Column} & \textbf{Type} & \textbf{Constraints} & \textbf{Purpose}\\
\midrule
\endfirsthead
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\small\itshape Table~\ref{tab:schema} continued}\\
\toprule
\textbf{Column} & \textbf{Type} & \textbf{Constraints} & \textbf{Purpose}\\
\midrule
\endhead
\bottomrule
\endfoot
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\cellcolor{amber!18}\textbf{departments} --- access-control backbone}\\
\code{id} & UUID & PK, \code{uuid4} & Surrogate key.\\
\code{name} & VARCHAR(100) & unique, not null & E.g. ``Human Resources''.\\
\code{description} & VARCHAR(500) & nullable & Admin-UI blurb.\\
\code{created\_at} & TIMESTAMPTZ & not null & Row creation.\\
\addlinespace
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\cellcolor{amber!18}\textbf{users} --- identity and role}\\
\code{id} & UUID & PK & Surrogate key.\\
\code{name} & VARCHAR(200) & not null & Display name.\\
\code{email} & VARCHAR(320) & unique, not null & Login id; 320 = RFC 5321 max.\\
\code{password\_hash} & VARCHAR(255) & not null & bcrypt digest --- never plaintext.\\
\code{department\_id} & UUID & FK, \emph{nullable} & Nullable for a global admin.\\
\code{role} & VARCHAR(20) & not null, def. \code{user} & \code{admin}/\code{user}/\code{viewer}.\\
\code{is\_active} & BOOLEAN & not null, def. true & Soft-delete flag.\\
\code{created\_at}, \code{updated\_at} & TIMESTAMPTZ & not null & \code{updated\_at} via \code{onupdate}.\\
\addlinespace
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\cellcolor{amber!18}\textbf{documents} --- one uploaded file}\\
\code{id} & UUID & PK & Surrogate key.\\
\code{filename} & VARCHAR(500) & not null & Sanitized internal name.\\
\code{original\_filename} & VARCHAR(500) & not null & Verbatim uploaded name.\\
\code{department\_id} & UUID & FK, not null & Owning department (RBAC).\\
\code{visibility} & VARCHAR(20) & not null, server-def. & \code{company}/\code{department}/\code{personal}.\\
\code{uploaded\_by} & UUID & FK, not null & Author; drives \code{personal} tier.\\
\code{status} & VARCHAR(20) & not null & \code{processing}/\code{ready}/\code{failed}.\\
\code{file\_size} & INTEGER & nullable & Bytes.\\
\code{page\_count} & INTEGER & nullable & Null for DOCX.\\
\code{chunk\_count} & INTEGER & nullable & Number of child chunks.\\
\code{summary} & TEXT & nullable & LLM summary.\\
\code{key\_points} & JSONB & nullable & List of strings.\\
\code{action\_items} & JSONB & nullable & List of \code{\{text,owner,deadline\}}.\\
\code{document\_type} & VARCHAR(20) & nullable & \code{policy}/\code{meeting\_notes}/\code{technical}/\code{other}.\\
\code{word\_count} & INTEGER & nullable & Computed in Python, not from LLM.\\
\code{error\_message} & TEXT & nullable & Set only when \code{failed}.\\
\code{created\_at}, \code{updated\_at} & TIMESTAMPTZ & not null & \\
\addlinespace
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\cellcolor{amber!18}\textbf{document\_chunks} --- hierarchical pieces}\\
\code{id} & UUID & PK & Surrogate key.\\
\code{document\_id} & UUID & FK \code{ON DELETE CASCADE} & No orphan chunks.\\
\code{chunk\_index} & INTEGER & not null & 0-based position.\\
\code{child\_text} & TEXT & not null & $\sim$256-token unit: embedded + retrieved.\\
\code{parent\_text} & TEXT & not null & $\sim$1024-token unit: sent to the LLM.\\
\code{page\_number} & INTEGER & nullable & Source page; null for DOCX.\\
\code{qdrant\_point\_id} & VARCHAR(36) & nullable & Links row to its Qdrant vector.\\
\code{created\_at} & TIMESTAMPTZ & not null & \\
\addlinespace
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\cellcolor{amber!18}\textbf{chat\_sessions} --- a conversation}\\
\code{id} & UUID & PK & Surrogate key.\\
\code{user\_id} & UUID & FK, not null & Owner.\\
\code{title} & VARCHAR(500) & nullable & LLM-auto-generated from first question.\\
\code{created\_at}, \code{updated\_at} & TIMESTAMPTZ & not null & \code{updated\_at} sorts the sidebar.\\
\addlinespace
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\cellcolor{amber!18}\textbf{chat\_messages} --- one turn}\\
\code{id} & UUID & PK & Surrogate key.\\
\code{session\_id} & UUID & FK \code{ON DELETE CASCADE} & Removed with its session.\\
\code{role} & VARCHAR(20) & not null & \code{user}/\code{assistant}.\\
\code{content} & TEXT & not null & Message text.\\
\code{sources} & JSONB & nullable & \code{\{filename,page,citation\_number\}} list.\\
\code{created\_at} & TIMESTAMPTZ & not null & \\
\addlinespace
\multicolumn{4}{l}{\cellcolor{amber!18}\textbf{query\_logs} --- analytics \& research record (denormalized)}\\
\code{id} & UUID & PK & Surrogate key.\\
\code{session\_id} & UUID & FK \code{ON DELETE SET NULL} & Survives session deletion.\\
\code{user\_id} & UUID & FK, not null & Who asked.\\
\code{department\_id} & UUID & FK, not null & Denormalized for group-by.\\
\code{query\_text} & TEXT & not null & Raw question.\\
\code{retrieval\_method} & VARCHAR(20) & nullable & \code{dense}/\code{hybrid}/\code{hybrid\_rerank}.\\
\code{faithfulness\_score} & FLOAT & nullable & RAGAS (offline eval).\\
\code{answer\_relevancy\_score} & FLOAT & nullable & RAGAS (reserved).\\
\code{context\_precision\_score} & FLOAT & nullable & RAGAS.\\
\code{answered} & BOOLEAN & not null, def. true & \code{false} on no-info refusal.\\
\code{response\_time\_ms} & INTEGER & nullable & End-to-end latency.\\
\code{created\_at} & TIMESTAMPTZ & not null & \\
\end{longtable}
\end{small}

\begin{keyidea}
\textbf{Three deliberate cascade choices.} \code{document\_chunks} and \code{chat\_messages} use
\textbf{CASCADE} (the child is meaningless without the parent); \code{query\_logs.session\_id}
uses \textbf{SET NULL} (the analytics record must outlive its conversation); and \code{users} is
never deleted---deactivation via \code{is\_active} preserves authorship of documents and queries.
\end{keyidea}

\section{Entity-Relationship Diagram}
Figure~\ref{fig:er} shows the seven entities, their key columns, and relationships labeled with
cardinality and on-delete behavior.

