\begin{keyidea}
\textbf{The dual store.} The relational schema is only half of where a document lives.
\code{document\_chunks} holds canonical text and a pointer (\code{qdrant\_point\_id}) to the
matching vector in Qdrant. The vector, its embeddings, and a denormalized copy of the chunk's
access metadata live in the Qdrant collection (Section~\ref{sec:qdrant}). Ingestion writes both;
reindexing reuses the stored point id so updates land in place.
\end{keyidea}

\section{The Ingestion Pipeline, End to End}
On upload, the HTTP handler (\code{routers/documents.py::upload\_document}) does only the fast
work---validate, persist a \code{processing} row, return \code{202 Accepted}---and schedules the
heavy lifting as a background task (\code{ingestion\_service.py::process\_document}). The client
then polls \code{GET /documents/\{id\}/status} until \code{ready} (Figure~\ref{fig:ingest}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=6mm and 10mm]
\node[box,minimum width=30mm] (up) {POST /upload\\\scriptsize (multipart)};
\node[decision, right=of up] (val) {validate};
\node[box, right=14mm of val, minimum width=26mm] (row) {Document row\\\scriptsize status=processing};
\node[box, below=10mm of row, minimum width=26mm] (acc) {202 Accepted};
\node[box, below=16mm of up, minimum width=26mm] (parse) {parse\_document};
\node[box, right=of parse, minimum width=24mm] (strip) {strip\\boilerplate};
\node[box, right=of strip, minimum width=22mm] (chunk) {hierarchical\\chunk};
\node[decision, below=10mm of chunk] (any) {chunks?};
\node[box, right=12mm of any, minimum width=22mm] (embed) {embed children\\\scriptsize Gemini 768d};
\node[box, below=10mm of embed, minimum width=24mm] (upsert) {upsert Qdrant\\\scriptsize dense+sparse};
\node[box, left=12mm of upsert, minimum width=26mm] (persist) {persist chunks\\\scriptsize status=ready};
\node[accentbox, below=10mm of parse, minimum width=26mm] (fail) {status=failed};
\draw[arr] (up)--(val); \draw[arr] (val)--node[lbl,above]{ok}(row);
\draw[arr] (val.south) to[bend right] node[lbl,left]{4xx}(acc);
\draw[arr] (row)--(acc);
\draw[arr] (row.south) to[bend left=10] node[lbl,right]{schedule}(parse.north);
\draw[arr] (parse)--(strip); \draw[arr] (strip)--(chunk); \draw[arr] (chunk)--(any);
\draw[arr] (any)--node[lbl,above]{yes}(embed);
\draw[arr] (any.south) to[bend right] node[lbl,left]{no}(fail);
\draw[arr] (embed)--(upsert); \draw[arr] (upsert)--(persist);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Document ingestion: a fast request path (202 + background task) and the background
pipeline parse $\rightarrow$ strip $\rightarrow$ chunk $\rightarrow$ embed $\rightarrow$ upsert
$\rightarrow$ persist, with the scanned-PDF failure branch.}
\label{fig:ingest}
\end{figure}

The orchestrator is wrapped so that on \emph{any} failure it marks the document \code{failed}
(in a separate DB session) and swallows the exception---a background task must never crash the
server. \code{hierarchical\_chunk} is deliberately \textbf{pure} (no DB/Gemini/Qdrant) so the
most correctness-critical logic is unit-testable in isolation.

\section{Parsing \& Boilerplate Stripping}
Each parser turns bytes into \code{\{text, page\}} dicts: \textbf{PDF} (PyMuPDF, 1-based page
numbers, skips image-only pages), \textbf{DOCX} (python-docx, \code{page = None} since Word has
no reliable page API), \textbf{PPTX} (python-pptx, 1-based slide numbers).

\textbf{Boilerplate stripping} (\code{\_strip\_boilerplate}) removes a repeated
letterhead/footer that would make chunks from \emph{different} documents look similar---diluting
embeddings and blunting the reranker. Two passes: a \textbf{frequency pass} drops lines appearing
on $>60\%$ of pages (requires $\geq 2$ pages), and a \textbf{pattern pass} drops the company name
(anchored), classification banners, bare page markers, footers ending in a page number, and short
($<4$-word) all-caps or colon-terminated labels. Pages that become empty are dropped.

\section{Hierarchical Chunking --- The Math}
\label{sec:chunk}
Pragya uses a hierarchical (parent/child) scheme to resolve a genuine tension: \emph{small chunks
retrieve precisely} (a 256-token chunk is tightly on-topic) while \emph{large chunks generate
well} (the LLM needs surrounding context). The resolution: \textbf{retrieve on children, generate
from parents}---each small child carries a pointer to its larger parent, and it is the parent text
the LLM reads.

Token counts are approximated by word counts (one token $\approx 0.75$ words):

\begin{align}
\text{CHILD\_WORDS} &= 341 \approx 256/0.75 \quad\text{(embedded + retrieved)}\\
\text{PARENT\_WORDS} &= 1365 \approx 1024/0.75 \quad\text{(sent to the LLM)}\\
\text{CHILD\_OVERLAP\_WORDS} &= 68 = 0.20 \times 341 \quad\text{(20\% overlap)}\\
\text{child\_step} &= 341 - 68 = 273 \quad\text{(advance per child)}
\end{align}

These are the literal constants in \code{ingestion\_service.py}. The 20\% child overlap guarantees
a short fact straddling a boundary survives whole in at least one child; parents do \emph{not}
overlap (they are context blocks, not match units). The algorithm flattens pages into a word
stream (keeping each word's source page so a child reports the page it \emph{starts} on), splits
into non-overlapping parents of up to 1365 words, then carves overlapping children of up to 341
words stepping by 273 (Figure~\ref{fig:chunkwin}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[xscale=0.85]
% word stream bar (one parent = 1365 words)
\draw[fill=paperbg, draw=ink] (0,0) rectangle (13.65,0.5);
\node[lbl] at (6.825,0.78) {Parent: words [0\,..\,1365) $\approx$ 1024 tokens (no overlap)};
% child windows
\foreach \s/\i in {0/0, 2.73/1, 5.46/2, 8.19/3, 10.92/4}{
  \draw[fill=amber!35, draw=amberdark] (\s,-0.6-0.0) rectangle ({min(\s+3.41,13.65)},-0.15);
  \node[font=\tiny] at ({\s+1.0},-0.38) {child \i};
}
\draw[decorate, decoration={brace, amplitude=4pt}, amberdark] (2.73,-0.72) -- (3.41,-0.72)
  node[midway, below, font=\tiny, color=amberdark]{68w overlap};
\node[lbl, anchor=west] at (0,-1.25) {Children: 341 words each, step 273 $\Rightarrow$ one full
parent yields 5 overlapping children.};
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Hierarchical chunking window. A 1365-word parent is sub-split into five 341-word children
that step forward by 273 words, overlapping their neighbour by 68 words (20\%). Children are
embedded; the parent is what the LLM reads.}
\label{fig:chunkwin}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Edge case.} If the entire document is $\leq 341$ words, the code uses the full text as
\emph{both} child and parent (one chunk, \code{chunk\_index = 0})---a one-paragraph memo still
yields exactly one well-formed chunk. With no extractable words (a scanned PDF), the function
returns empty and the document fails with a clear message.

\begin{divergence}
\code{CLAUDE.md} specifies child = 256 tokens, parent = 1024 tokens. The implementation
approximates tokens with words at the 0.75 ratio (341/1365 words). The trade-off (no tokenizer
dependency, fully deterministic, unit-testable) is intentional; a token-dense chunk may slightly
exceed the nominal token budget.
\end{divergence}

\section{Embedding --- Gemini \& Matryoshka}
The \emph{child} texts (the retrieval unit) are embedded by \code{embed\_chunks()}:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Model + dims from config:} \code{gemini-embedding-001} at \code{output\_dimensionality
  = 768}.
  \item \textbf{Matryoshka 3072$\to$768:} the 768-d prefix is itself valid because the model is
  trained with nested representations. This shrinks the index $\sim$4$\times$. No re-normalization
  is needed (cosine distance is scale-invariant).
  \item \textbf{Asymmetric task type:} documents use \code{task\_type="retrieval\_document"}; the
  query side uses \code{"retrieval\_query"}. Mixing them silently degrades retrieval---a classic
  invisible RAG bug---so the two constants live in separate modules.
  \item \textbf{Batching:} groups of \code{EMBEDDING\_BATCH\_SIZE = 20} with a 1\,s pause between
  batches (free-tier discipline); the blocking call runs via \code{asyncio.to\_thread}.
\end{itemize}

\section{The Qdrant Collection}
\label{sec:qdrant}
All vectors live in one collection, \code{pragya\_docs}, created once at startup (idempotent).
It is configured with two \textbf{named vectors} per point:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,caption={Named dense + sparse vector configuration (qdrant.py).}]
vectors_config        = {"dense":  VectorParams(size=768, distance=COSINE, on_disk=False)}
sparse_vectors_config = {"sparse": SparseVectorParams(index=SparseIndexParams(on_disk=False))}
# payload keyword indexes (O(1) RBAC filtering): department_id, visibility, uploaded_by
\end{lstlisting}

Each point's payload carries \code{document\_id}, \code{department\_id}, \code{visibility},
\code{uploaded\_by}, \code{chunk\_index}, \code{parent\_text}, \code{source\_filename}, and
\code{page\_number}. Two design points: the \textbf{parent text is stored in the payload} (so
generation needs no second DB round-trip), and the access metadata is \textbf{denormalized into
every point} (so the access filter runs entirely inside the Qdrant query). Three payload fields
(\code{department\_id}, \code{visibility}, \code{uploaded\_by}) get a keyword index, and all UUIDs
are stored \emph{as strings}---Qdrant's \code{MatchValue} compares by exact type, so a raw
\code{uuid.UUID} would match zero points with no error.

\section{The Sparse Channel \& Its Honest Limitations}
\label{sec:sparse}
Pragya implements a sparse (keyword) vector intended as a BM25-style signal. This section documents
how it is built \emph{and} a real defect the evaluation exposed.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,caption={Sparse vector construction --- ingestion vs.\ query (note the divergence).}]
# INGESTION (build_sparse_vector, ingestion_service.py)
index = abs(hash(word)) % 100_000      # index space = 100,000
value = count(word) / total_tokens     # normalized term frequency

# QUERY (sparse_retrieve, retrieval_service.py)
index = abs(hash(word)) % 30_000       # index space = 30,000 (SPARSE_INDEX_SPACE)
value = raw count(word)                # unnormalized term frequency
\end{lstlisting}

A sparse dot product contributes a non-zero score only when a query index and a stored index
\emph{coincide}. They do not, for two independent reasons:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Index-space mismatch (100{,}000 vs 30{,}000).} \code{abs(hash(w)) \% 100000} and
  \code{abs(hash(w)) \% 30000} are equal only by coincidence.
  \item \textbf{Per-process hash salting.} Python's built-in \code{hash()} for strings is
  randomized per process (\code{PYTHONHASHSEED}). Ingestion and querying run in different
  processes, so the same word hashes differently---meaning that \emph{even if the moduli matched},
  the indices would still not align.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{observation}
The sparse channel contributes essentially \textbf{no real keyword matches} in the current build;
dense retrieval carries the system. This is exactly consistent with the evaluation
(Chapter~\ref{ch:eval}), where \emph{hybrid} scores almost identically to \emph{dense}
($0.907$ vs $0.905$): if sparse were contributing real signal, hybrid would separate further. The
fusion machinery (RRF) is correct and fully wired---it is simply fusing a strong dense list with a
near-empty sparse list. The fix (a stable hash such as \code{hashlib}, or a learned sparse encoder
like SPLADE) is recorded in Chapter~\ref{ch:journey}. The defect is documented rather than quietly
patched so the Chapter~\ref{ch:eval} numbers remain attributable to the system that was measured.
\end{observation}

%==============================================================================
\chapter{Retrieval Pipeline --- The Research Core}
\label{ch:retrieval}
%==============================================================================

Everything in \code{services/retrieval\_service.py} answers one question well: \emph{given a
user's question and their access rights, which passages should the LLM read before answering?}
The module implements three pipelines behind one entry point, \code{retrieve(query,
current\_user, method, document\_id)}. Two invariants run through every function: \textbf{asymmetric
embedding} (query uses \code{retrieval\_query}, documents used \code{retrieval\_document}) and
\textbf{access control on every search} (the visibility filter, Chapter~\ref{ch:generation}).

\section{The Full Query Pipeline}
Figure~\ref{fig:query} traces a question through the full pipeline (\code{hybrid\_rerank}, used by
chat). Simpler methods are this pipeline with later stages removed.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=6mm and 12mm]
\node[box,minimum width=30mm] (q) {Question + User};
\node[accentbox, below=8mm of q, minimum width=34mm] (filt) {3-tier visibility filter};
\node[box, below=8mm of filt, minimum width=30mm] (emb) {embed\_query\\\scriptsize 768d, retrieval\_query};
\node[box, below left=10mm and 0mm of emb, minimum width=28mm] (dense) {dense\_retrieve\\\scriptsize cosine, top 20};
\node[box, below right=10mm and 0mm of emb, minimum width=28mm] (sparse) {sparse\_retrieve\\\scriptsize BM25-style, top 20};
\node[box, below=22mm of emb, minimum width=30mm] (rrf) {rrf\_fusion\\\scriptsize $k{=}60$, dedup, cap 40};
\node[box, below=8mm of rrf, minimum width=30mm] (rr) {rerank\\\scriptsize cross-encoder, top 5};
\node[accentbox, below=8mm of rr, minimum width=34mm] (out) {Top-5 parents $\to$ generation};
\draw[arr] (q)--(filt); \draw[arr] (filt)--(emb);
\draw[arr] (emb) -- (dense); \draw[arr] (emb) -- (sparse);
\draw[arr] (dense) -- (rrf); \draw[arr] (sparse) -- (rrf);
\draw[arr] (rrf)--(rr); \draw[arr] (rr)--(out);
\draw[darr] (filt.east) to[bend left=55] node[lbl,right]{shared by both retrievers} (sparse.east);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{The full query pipeline. The visibility filter is built once and shared by both
retrievers; dense + sparse feed RRF, which feeds the cross-encoder reranker.}
\label{fig:query}
\end{figure}

\section{Dense Retrieval --- Cosine Similarity}
Dense retrieval compares the query vector against each accessible document's \code{dense} vector by
\textbf{cosine similarity} and returns the top 20:

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{cosine}(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{d}) = \frac{\mathbf{q}\cdot\mathbf{d}}{\lVert\mathbf{q}\rVert\,\lVert\mathbf{d}\rVert}
= \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{768} q_i d_i}{\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{768} q_i^2}\,\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^{768} d_i^2}} \in [-1,1]
\end{equation}

Qdrant computes this (the \code{dense} vector is configured \code{Distance.COSINE}) and returns it
as each point's score. \textbf{Top 20 is deliberately generous:} dense and sparse each contribute 20
candidates so RRF has a real pool and the reranker has enough to choose from. Retrieval favors
recall; precision is recovered later. Dense retrieval is also used directly by document search
(Section~\ref{sec:search}).

\section{Sparse Retrieval --- BM25-Style Matching}
Sparse retrieval catches exact keyword matches dense retrieval misses. Qdrant scores a sparse query
against stored sparse vectors by a dot product over shared indices:

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{score}_{\text{sparse}}(\mathbf{q},\mathbf{d}) = \sum_{i \,\in\, \mathrm{idx}(\mathbf{q})\,\cap\,\mathrm{idx}(\mathbf{d})} q_i \cdot d_i
\end{equation}

where $\mathrm{idx}(\cdot)$ is the set of non-zero indices. Only indices present in both contribute
---exactly keyword overlap. (As established in Section~\ref{sec:sparse}, the channel runs but finds
few real intersections in the current build; the mathematics is correct.)

\section{RRF Fusion --- Formula \& Worked Example}
Dense and sparse produce two ranked lists whose raw scores are not comparable (a cosine $\approx
0.7$ vs a sparse dot product of $3.0$). \textbf{Reciprocal Rank Fusion} ignores raw scores and uses
only rank:

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{RRF}(d) = \sum_{L \,\in\, \{\text{dense},\,\text{sparse}\}} \frac{1}{k + \mathrm{rank}_L(d)}, \qquad k = 60
\end{equation}

where $\mathrm{rank}_L(d)$ is the 1-based position of $d$ in list $L$, and an absent document
contributes nothing from that list. \textbf{Why $k=60$:} it dampens the very top ranks
($\tfrac{1}{61}\approx 0.01639$ vs $\tfrac{1}{62}\approx 0.01613$), so no single list dominates
merely because one item ranked first. 60 is the standard default (Cormack et al., 2009); beyond it,
RRF is \textbf{parameter-free}. Because contributions \emph{sum}, a document ranked well in
\emph{both} lists beats one ranked \#1 in only one---rewarding cross-method agreement.

\textbf{Worked example.} Two ranked lists over five chunks A--E:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{RRF worked example: two ranked lists fuse into one ($k=60$).}
\label{tab:rrf}
\begin{tabular}{c c c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Chunk} & \textbf{Dense contribution} & \textbf{Sparse contribution} & \textbf{RRF score} & \textbf{Final rank}\\
\midrule
\textbf{A} & rank 1 $\to 1/61=0.01639$ & rank 2 $\to 1/62=0.01613$ & \textbf{0.03252} & \textbf{1}\\
\textbf{C} & rank 3 $\to 1/63=0.01587$ & rank 1 $\to 1/61=0.01639$ & \textbf{0.03227} & \textbf{2}\\
\textbf{B} & rank 2 $\to 1/62=0.01613$ & rank 4 $\to 1/64=0.01563$ & \textbf{0.03175} & \textbf{3}\\
E & --- (absent) & rank 3 $\to 1/63=0.01587$ & 0.01587 & 4\\
D & rank 4 $\to 1/64=0.01563$ & --- (absent) & 0.01563 & 5\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=12cm, height=5.2cm, ybar, bar width=14pt,
  ymin=0, ymax=0.035, ylabel={RRF score},
  symbolic x coords={A,C,B,E,D}, xtick=data,
  nodes near coords, nodes near coords style={font=\tiny},
  every node near coord/.append style={/pgf/number format/fixed, /pgf/number format/precision=5},
  enlarge x limits=0.12, ymajorgrids, tick label style={font=\small},
]
\addplot[fill=amber, draw=amberdark] coordinates {(A,0.03252)(C,0.03227)(B,0.03175)(E,0.01587)(D,0.01563)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Fused RRF scores from Table~\ref{tab:rrf}. A and C---ranked well in \emph{both} lists---rise
to the top; D and E, strong in only one list, sink. Fusion rewards cross-method agreement with no
tunable weights.}
\label{fig:rrfchart}
\end{figure}

The implementation accumulates these scores in a dict keyed by \code{qdrant\_id} (so deduplication is
automatic), sorts descending, and \textbf{caps the pool at 40}---enough for the reranker without
cross-encoding an unbounded list.

\section{Cross-Encoder Reranking}
The final stage re-scores fused candidates with a cross-encoder and keeps the best five.

\begin{align}
\text{bi-encoder:}\quad & \mathrm{sim}_{\text{bi}}(q,d) = \mathrm{cosine}\big(\mathrm{Enc}(q),\,\mathrm{Enc}(d)\big)\\
\text{cross-encoder:}\quad & \mathrm{score}_{\text{cross}}(q,d) = \mathrm{Transformer}\big(\texttt{[CLS]}\,q\,\texttt{[SEP]}\,d\,\texttt{[SEP]}\big) \to \mathbb{R}
\end{align}

A bi-encoder embeds query and document \emph{independently} (cheap; nothing precomputable is lost
because everything is precomputed). A cross-encoder feeds the \emph{pair} through the transformer
together, letting attention relate every query token to every document token---far more accurate but
costly, which is why it runs only on the $\sim$40 fused candidates. Pragya uses
\code{cross-encoder/ms-marco-MiniLM-L-6-v2} (sentence-transformers, $\sim$85\,MB, loaded once into a
module-level singleton). It scores \code{(query, parent\_text)} pairs---\emph{not} \code{child\_text}
---because the parent is what the LLM actually reads, then keeps the top 5.

\begin{observation}
\textbf{Reranking is not a free lunch.} Intuitively a cross-encoder should only help. On Pragya's
corpus it does \emph{not}: \code{hybrid\_rerank} scores lowest of the three methods, with faithfulness
dropping to $0.75$. The likely mechanism is \textbf{over-pruning}---cutting aggressively to top-5
parents sometimes drops a context block the answer needed, and an answer missing a source scores
worse on faithfulness. Full treatment in Section~\ref{sec:findings}.
\end{observation}

\section{The Three Methods as Configurations}
All three experiments are the same pipeline truncated at different stages (Table~\ref{tab:methods}).

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{The three retrieval methods as pipeline configurations.}
\label{tab:methods}
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{X c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Stage} & \textbf{dense (A)} & \textbf{hybrid (B)} & \textbf{hybrid\_rerank (C)}\\
\midrule
Embed query (asymmetric) & \checkmark & \checkmark & \checkmark\\
Dense retrieve (top 20, cosine) & \checkmark & \checkmark & \checkmark\\
Sparse retrieve (top 20, BM25-style) & --- & \checkmark & \checkmark\\
RRF fusion ($k{=}60$, cap 40) & --- & \checkmark & \checkmark\\
Cross-encoder rerank (top 5) & --- & --- & \checkmark\\
\midrule
Typical output cardinality & up to 20 & up to 40 & exactly 5\\
Relative cost & 1 embed + 1 search & 1 embed + 2 searches & + $\sim$40 cross-enc.\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

In the running system, chat uses \code{hybrid\_rerank} (\code{CHAT\_RETRIEVAL\_METHOD}), document
search uses \code{dense} directly, and all three are compared head-to-head only by the evaluation
harness.

\begin{keyidea}
\textbf{The K-asymmetry caveat.} The methods return different numbers of contexts (dense $\approx 8$
deduped parents, hybrid $\approx 12$, rerank exactly 5). A fair metric comparison cannot score ``all
returned contexts.'' The evaluation caps scoring to a fixed top-3 (context precision) and top-2
(faithfulness), turning the comparison into a clean precision@$K$ across all three methods
(Chapter~\ref{ch:eval}).
\end{keyidea}

%==============================================================================
\chapter{Generation, Citations \& Access Control}
\label{ch:generation}
%==============================================================================

Retrieval found the relevant parent chunks; this chapter turns them into a grounded, cited answer
that streams to the user, and covers the access-control system that decided which chunks the user
could see.

\section{Citation-Enforced Generation}
The single most important generation decision: the model is \textbf{forbidden from using any
knowledge outside the retrieved context}. \code{build\_citation\_prompt()} assembles the prompt in
four parts---system rules, optional conversation history, numbered context blocks, the question. The
system instructions (verbatim from the code):

\begin{lstlisting}[language=none,caption={The five-line system contract (generation\_service.py).}]
You are Pragya, a precise knowledge assistant.
Answer ONLY using the provided context blocks.
Cite every factual claim using [Source: N] where N is the context block number.
If the answer is not in the context respond with exactly: I don't have information on
  this in your department's documents.
Do not infer, extrapolate, or use outside knowledge.
\end{lstlisting}

Three of the five lines exist purely to suppress hallucination, converting open-ended generation into
a \textbf{closed-book-over-provided-context} task: the model's job is reduced to reading and
attributing, not recalling. The retrieved chunks are then emitted as numbered blocks, each a 1-based
number, a \code{Source:} line (filename + page if present), and the block's \emph{parent} text:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=none,caption={Numbered context-block layout fed to Gemini.}]
Context blocks:
[1] Source: HR_Leave_Policy_2025.pdf, Page 4
<the full parent_text of the top chunk>

[2] Source: IT_Security_Policy_2025.pdf, Page 2
<the full parent_text of the next chunk>
...
Question: How many casual leaves do I get?
Answer:
\end{lstlisting}

The block numbers are load-bearing: after generation, \code{extract\_sources()} finds every
\code{[Source: N]} (regex \code{\textbackslash[Source:\textbackslash s*(\textbackslash d+)\textbackslash]}),
looks up \code{chunks[N-1]}, and pulls the real filename + page, deduplicated by
\code{(filename, page)}; a hallucinated out-of-range $N$ is skipped. The result is persisted in
\code{chat\_messages.sources} and rendered as citation chips.

\begin{keyidea}
\textbf{The fixed refusal is a three-way contract.} The exact string \code{NO\_INFO\_RESPONSE} is
defined once and reused in three places that must never drift: (1) the prompt instructs the model to
emit it verbatim, (2) the chat router streams it when retrieval returns no chunks, and (3)
\code{response\_indicates\_no\_info()} matches it to set \code{query\_logs.answered = False}. A
one-character drift would mislabel analytics.
\end{keyidea}

\section{Parent Deduplication Before Generation}
Overlapping children frequently map to the same parent, so the top-$k$ can contain near-identical
parent blocks---wasting tokens and inducing over-citation (\code{[Source: 1,2,3,4,5]} for one fact).
\code{\_dedupe\_by\_parent()} keys each chunk on the first 200 characters of its \code{parent\_text}
and keeps the first occurrence, preserving order. It is shared by \emph{both}
\code{build\_citation\_prompt()} (to number blocks) and \code{extract\_sources()} (to resolve
\code{[Source: N]})---they must dedupe identically or the citation numbers would not line up.

\section{SSE Streaming \& Turn Persistence}
A grounded answer over five parents takes seconds; streaming tokens as they arrive makes the product
feel alive. \code{generate\_stream()} calls Gemini with \code{stream=True} and yields one SSE frame
\code{data: <token>} per token, with two sentinels: \code{[DONE]} (clean finish) and
\code{[ERROR] <msg>} (failed mid-stream, e.g. a free-tier 429). Because a streaming response has
already sent its \code{200 OK} headers, an error can only be signaled \textbf{in-band}.

The streaming + persistence ordering (Figure~\ref{fig:sse}) is the subtle part:

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=5mm and 14mm]
\node[box,minimum width=34mm] (a) {Commit session + USER message\\\scriptsize (before returning)};
\node[box, below=of a, minimum width=34mm] (b) {retrieve() grounding chunks};
\node[accentbox, below=of b, minimum width=34mm] (c) {Return 200 + SSE headers};
\node[box, below=of c, minimum width=34mm] (d) {Stream token frames $\to$ client};
\node[box, below=of d, minimum width=34mm] (e) {\code{[DONE]}};
\node[box, below=of e, minimum width=46mm] (f) {(fresh session) ASSISTANT message\\ + query log + auto-title\\\scriptsize errors swallowed --- response already sent};
\draw[arr] (a)--(b); \draw[arr] (b)--(c); \draw[arr] (c)--(d); \draw[arr] (d)--(e); \draw[arr] (e)--(f);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Streaming + persistence ordering. The user message is committed before the response; the
assistant message, query log, and title are written \emph{after} \code{[DONE]} in a fresh DB session.}
\label{fig:sse}
\end{figure}

On the \textbf{no-chunks} path the router streams \code{NO\_INFO\_RESPONSE} and logs
\code{answered=False}; on the \textbf{error} path it logs \code{answered=False} but persists no blank
assistant message (an empty bubble would render broken, and \code{answered} feeds the research table).
The auto-title is a best-effort second Gemini call that falls back to the question's first words.

\section{The 3-Tier Visibility Model}
\label{sec:visibility}
Access control is enforced at the \textbf{vector-DB layer} (retrieval) and the \textbf{application
layer} (listing, status, intelligence, reindex). Three tiers live on \code{documents.visibility},
denormalized into every Qdrant payload (Table~\ref{tab:tiers}).

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{The three visibility tiers.}
\label{tab:tiers}
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{l X l}
\toprule
\textbf{Tier} & \textbf{Who can access} & \textbf{Who creates}\\
\midrule
\code{company} & All authenticated users, any department & Admins only\\
\code{department} & Users whose \code{department\_id} matches (default) & Any user (own dept)\\
\code{personal} & Only the uploader (\code{uploaded\_by == user.id}) --- not even admins & Any user\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\code{build\_visibility\_filter()} expresses ``retrievable if any tier grants access'' as a Qdrant
\code{should} (OR) of three \code{must} (AND) sub-filters:

\begin{equation}
\mathrm{retrievable}(c) =
\underbrace{(v_c{=}\texttt{company})}_{\text{tier 1}}
\;\lor\;
\underbrace{(v_c{=}\texttt{department} \wedge \mathrm{dept}_c{=}\mathrm{dept}_u)}_{\text{tier 2}}
\;\lor\;
\underbrace{(v_c{=}\texttt{personal} \wedge \mathrm{owner}_c{=}u)}_{\text{tier 3}}
\end{equation}

Because the filter is part of \emph{every} retrieval query, a forbidden chunk is never a candidate
(Figure~\ref{fig:visibility}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=6mm and 14mm]
\node[box] (s) {chunk $c$ for user $u$};
\node[decision, below=8mm of s] (v) {visibility?};
\node[accentbox, right=22mm of v] (yes) {retrievable};
\node[box, below=14mm of v] (dept) {dept$_c$ = dept$_u$?};
\node[decision, left=14mm of dept] (pers) {owner$_c$ = $u$?};
\node[box, below=8mm of dept] (no) {filtered out};
\draw[arr] (s)--(v);
\draw[arr] (v)--node[lbl,above]{company}(yes);
\draw[arr] (v)--node[lbl,right]{department}(dept);
\draw[arr] (v.west) to[bend right=12] node[lbl,above]{personal}(pers.north);
\draw[arr] (dept.east) to[bend right=20] node[lbl,right]{yes}(yes.south);
\draw[arr] (dept)--node[lbl,right]{no}(no);
\draw[arr] (pers.south) to[bend right] node[lbl,left]{yes}(yes.west);
\draw[arr] (pers) to[bend left=10] node[lbl,left]{no}(no.west);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Per-chunk visibility decision. \code{company} is always retrievable; \code{department} and
\code{personal} require a department or owner match respectively.}
\label{fig:visibility}
\end{figure}

The department and user ids are \textbf{stringified} for the filter. The retrieval filter
deliberately has \textbf{no admin branch}: for retrieval, an admin is scoped to their own department
like anyone else. The \textbf{application layer} (\code{can\_access\_document}) is where the admin
asymmetry lives: \code{company} $\to$ everyone, \code{personal} $\to$ only the uploader,
\code{department} $\to$ an admin may access \emph{any} department's dept-docs, everyone else only
their own. Creating a \code{company} document is admin-gated at upload (else \code{403}).

\section{JWT Authentication \& the RBAC Dependency Chain}
Authentication is stateless JWTs; there are no server-side sessions. Passwords are bcrypt-hashed (salt
stored inside the hash; constant-time verify). \code{create\_access\_token()} mints:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=none,caption={JWT payload (auth\_service.py), signed HS256, 8-hour expiry.}]
{
  "sub":           "<user_id>",                 # subject (UUID as string)
  "department_id": "<department_id>" | null,     # the RBAC boundary; real null if absent
  "role":          "admin" | "user" | "viewer",
  "exp":           <now + 8 hours>,              # UTC-aware
  "iat":           <now>                         # issued-at
}
\end{lstlisting}

UUIDs are stringified (\code{jwt.encode} runs \code{json.dumps}, which cannot serialize a UUID), and a
null \code{department\_id} is a real JSON \code{null}, never the string \code{"None"} (which would
poison the RBAC filter). Authorization is a chain of FastAPI dependencies (Figure~\ref{fig:auth}):

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=8mm]
\node[box,minimum width=24mm] (tok) {Bearer JWT};
\node[box, right=10mm of tok, minimum width=24mm] (dec) {decode\_token\\\scriptsize sig + expiry (401)};
\node[box, right=10mm of dec, minimum width=30mm] (gcu) {get\_current\_user\\\scriptsize load active user (401/404)};
\node[accentbox, right=10mm of gcu, minimum width=24mm] (adm) {require\_admin\\\scriptsize 403 if not admin};
\node[box, below=8mm of gcu, minimum width=30mm] (h1) {protected route};
\node[box, below=8mm of adm, minimum width=24mm] (h2) {admin route};
\draw[arr] (tok)--(dec); \draw[arr] (dec)--(gcu); \draw[arr] (gcu)--(adm);
\draw[arr] (gcu)--(h1); \draw[arr] (adm)--(h2);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{The RBAC dependency chain. \code{get\_current\_user} folds the \code{is\_active} check into
its query (a deactivated user loses access on the next request everywhere); \code{require\_admin}
layers a role gate on top.}
\label{fig:auth}
\end{figure}

A logged-in non-admin gets \code{403} (forbidden), distinct from the \code{401} an anonymous caller
gets. Login returns an identical \code{401} whether the email is unknown or the password wrong---no
email enumeration.

%==============================================================================
\chapter{Feature Modules}
\label{ch:features}
%==============================================================================

This chapter walks through every feature module built on the foundation of Chapters~\ref{ch:data}--%
\ref{ch:generation}: purpose, mechanism, endpoints, and data flow.

\section{Auth \& Onboarding}
\label{sec:auth}
\textbf{Purpose.} Get a new employee from ``no account'' to ``querying their department's documents''
while bootstrapping an empty organization without a chicken-and-egg deadlock. Onboarding is a
two-step flow---create an account, then join a department---because the department is the RBAC
boundary and a new organization has no departments or admins yet (Figure~\ref{fig:onboard}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=6mm and 12mm]
\node[box,minimum width=26mm] (reg) {POST /auth/register};
\node[decision, right=of reg] (first) {first user?};
\node[accentbox, above right=4mm and 12mm of first, minimum width=20mm] (admin) {role=admin};
\node[box, below right=4mm and 12mm of first, minimum width=20mm] (user) {role=user};
\node[box, below=14mm of first, minimum width=26mm] (getd) {GET /departments};
\node[box, below=8mm of getd, minimum width=30mm] (pick) {pick or (admin) create dept};
\node[box, below=8mm of pick, minimum width=34mm] (patch) {PATCH /auth/me\\\scriptsize saveToken(fresh JWT)};
\node[accentbox, below=8mm of patch, minimum width=24mm] (chat) {$\to$ /chat};
\draw[arr] (reg)--(first);
\draw[arr] (first)--node[lbl]{yes}(admin);
\draw[arr] (first)--node[lbl]{no}(user);
\draw[arr] (first)--(getd);
\draw[arr] (getd)--(pick); \draw[arr] (pick)--(patch); \draw[arr] (patch)--(chat);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Two-step onboarding. The first user ever is auto-promoted to admin; step 2 self-assigns a
department and saves a fresh JWT carrying the new \code{department\_id}.}
\label{fig:onboard}
\end{figure}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Auth \& department endpoints.}
\label{tab:authendpoints}
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{l X}
\toprule
\textbf{Endpoint} & \textbf{Notable behavior}\\
\midrule
\code{POST /auth/register} & Email-uniqueness $\to$ clean 409; first user $\to$ admin (counted before insert); returns JWT (registration doubles as login).\\
\code{POST /auth/login} & Uniform 401 (no email enumeration).\\
\code{GET /auth/me} & Hydrate auth state.\\
\code{PATCH /auth/me} & Self-assign department (404 if missing); role change admin-only (403); returns a \emph{fresh} JWT.\\
\code{POST /departments} & Bootstrap: any user while the table is empty, else admin-only; 409 on duplicate.\\
\code{GET /departments} & Any authenticated user (drives the signup picker).\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\textbf{Why the fresh token on \code{PATCH /auth/me}.} The JWT carries \code{department\_id}, and most
requests authorize from the token without a DB hit. Returning a fresh token (which the frontend saves
before navigating) makes the new department effective immediately rather than at token expiry.

\section{Document Intelligence}
\label{sec:intel}
\textbf{Purpose.} Turn an ingested document into a structured brief: a 3--5 sentence summary, 5--7 key
points, action items, a coarse type, and a word count. Three ideas make it cheap and robust:
\textbf{reconstruct, don't re-parse} (rebuild text from stored \code{child\_text} chunks---free, no
Gemini/PyMuPDF); \textbf{map-reduce for long documents} (above 4000 words); \textbf{trust Python for
the count} (\code{word\_count = len(text.split())}; the LLM's count is ignored). The flow is
idempotent---if a summary already exists it skips (Figure~\ref{fig:mapreduce}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=6mm and 12mm]
\node[box,minimum width=30mm] (run) {run\_intelligence\\\scriptsize background, own session};
\node[decision, below=8mm of run] (ready) {ready \&\\no summary?};
\node[box, right=16mm of ready, minimum width=22mm] (skip) {skip (idempotent)};
\node[box, below=10mm of ready, minimum width=30mm] (text) {get\_document\_text\\\scriptsize from child chunks};
\node[decision, below=8mm of text] (long) {$\geq$ 4000\\words?};
\node[box, left=14mm of long, minimum width=24mm] (single) {single call};
\node[box, right=14mm of long, minimum width=30mm] (map) {MAP: each section\\$\to$ 2--3 sentences};
\node[box, below=8mm of map, minimum width=30mm] (reduce) {REDUCE: combine\\$\to$ final extraction};
\node[box, below=18mm of long, minimum width=42mm] (persist) {parse JSON, overwrite word\_count,\\persist 5 fields};
\draw[arr] (run)--(ready);
\draw[arr] (ready)--node[lbl,above]{no}(skip);
\draw[arr] (ready)--node[lbl,right]{yes}(text);
\draw[arr] (text)--(long);
\draw[arr] (long)--node[lbl,above]{short}(single);
\draw[arr] (long)--node[lbl,above]{long}(map);
\draw[arr] (map)--(reduce);
\draw[arr] (single) to[bend right=10] (persist.west);
\draw[arr] (reduce) to[bend left=10] (persist.east);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Document intelligence with the map-reduce branch for long documents. Short documents take a
single extraction call; long ones summarize section-by-section first.}
\label{fig:mapreduce}
\end{figure}

The extraction prompt demands valid JSON (\code{summary}, \code{key\_points}, \code{action\_items},
\code{document\_type}, \code{word\_count}); parsing is defensive (\code{\_strip\_code\_fences}, graceful
degradation on \code{JSONDecodeError}). Endpoints: \code{POST /intelligence/\{id\}} returns 200 + the
result if cached, else 202 + scheduled; \code{GET /intelligence/\{id\}} returns 404 until generated.
Both enforce \code{can\_access\_document}, so a \code{personal} document's intelligence is visible only
to its uploader.

\section{Meeting Assistant}
\textbf{Purpose.} Turn a raw transcript into structured output---summary, decisions, owned action
items (each with a \code{priority}), participants, an estimated duration, and follow-up questions---in
a single Gemini call. No persistence (ephemeral). \code{\_safe\_parse()} strips fences and validates
with Pydantic, falling back to a minimal valid response. Transcripts above \code{\_MAX\_WORDS = 6000}
are truncated with a note. Endpoints: \code{POST /meeting/process} (pasted text) and
\code{POST /meeting/upload} (\code{.txt} decoded UTF-8, or \code{.pdf} via the ingestion
\code{parse\_pdf}); the router owns file extraction, the service owns intelligence extraction.

\section{Document Search}
\label{sec:search}
\textbf{Purpose.} A fast semantic search for finding \emph{where} something is (vs chat's
\emph{answering}). \code{GET /documents/search} is the dense path used directly: embed the query, run
one dense Qdrant search under the \emph{same} 3-tier visibility filter, retrieve a pool of 30, group
to at most 2 chunks per document, return the top $N$ (default 10). Preview is the first 200 chars of
\code{parent\_text}; a user with no department gets an empty list.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=4mm and 12mm]
\node[box,minimum width=26mm] (q) {GET /search?q};
\node[box, right=of q, minimum width=22mm] (e) {embed\_query};
\node[box, right=of e, minimum width=30mm] (d) {dense top 30\\\scriptsize + visibility filter};
\node[box, right=of d, minimum width=26mm] (g) {$\leq$ 2 / doc};
\node[accentbox, right=of g, minimum width=22mm] (r) {top $N$};
\draw[arr] (q)--(e); \draw[arr] (e)--(d); \draw[arr] (d)--(g); \draw[arr] (g)--(r);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Document search: dense retrieval reused directly, visibility-filtered, capped at two chunks
per document.}
\label{fig:search}
\end{figure}

\section{Conversation History}
\textbf{Purpose.} Persist conversations and give chat multi-turn memory. Before saving a new user
message, the handler loads the most recent \code{HISTORY\_LIMIT = 4} messages and replays the last
\code{MAX\_HISTORY\_TURNS = 4} turns as \code{Human:}/\code{Assistant:} lines (loading before saving
keeps the current question out of its own context). Endpoints: \code{GET /chat/sessions} (most-recent
first, with a message-count sub-query and a first-user-message preview),
\code{GET /chat/sessions/\{id\}/messages} (owner-only, oldest-first), and
\code{DELETE /chat/sessions/\{id\}} (owner-only; \code{chat\_messages} CASCADE, \code{query\_logs}
SET NULL).

\section{Analytics Dashboard}
\label{sec:analytics}
\textbf{Purpose.} A read-only admin view of platform usage. Every endpoint requires
\code{require\_admin}; the data source is the denormalized \code{query\_logs} plus
\code{documents}/\code{users}/\code{departments} (Table~\ref{tab:analytics}).

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{The six analytics endpoints.}
\label{tab:analytics}
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{l X}
\toprule
\textbf{Endpoint} & \textbf{What it returns / data source}\\
\midrule
\code{/analytics/overview} & Headline cards: total/answered/unanswered queries, ready docs, active users, departments, avg response time, avg faithfulness. Scalar aggregates.\\
\code{/analytics/top-queries} & Most-repeated topics, grouped by the first 60 chars of \code{query\_text}.\\
\code{/analytics/unanswered} & Recent \code{answered=False} questions, joined to department name --- the ``what documents are missing'' signal.\\
\code{/analytics/document-usage} & Documents ranked by \code{chunk\_count} (a size proxy; true hit-counts would need parsing \code{sources} JSONB).\\
\code{/analytics/queries-over-time} & Daily counts for 30 days, zero-filled in Python so the chart has no gaps.\\
\code{/analytics/department-activity} & Per-department query/doc/user counts --- three separate GROUP BYs stitched in Python (a single join would multiply one-to-many rows).\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

The \code{avg\_faithfulness} card averages \code{query\_logs.faithfulness\_score}, populated by the
offline RAGAS evaluation (Chapter~\ref{ch:eval}), not at query time.

\section{Admin Panel}
\textbf{Purpose.} Manage the two things that drive access control: users (and roles) and departments.
All endpoints are \code{require\_admin}-gated; queries avoid N+1 patterns. \code{GET /admin/users}
(one join for department names), \code{GET /admin/departments} (one grouped count), and
\code{PATCH /admin/users/\{id\}/role} (validates the role, 404 if missing, and \textbf{guards against
an admin stripping their own admin role}---a 400---which would lock them out of the dashboard).

%==============================================================================
\chapter{Frontend Architecture}
\label{ch:frontend}
%==============================================================================

The frontend is a Next.js 15 application providing every user-facing surface. It obeys one hard rule:
\textbf{the frontend never touches a database}---it talks only to the FastAPI backend through one
client module (\code{lib/api.ts}). Everything security-relevant is enforced server-side; the client's
job is presentation.

\section{Next.js 15 App Router Structure}
The app uses the App Router (file-system routing under \code{app/}), React 19, and React Server
Components by default, with \code{"use client"} opting interactive trees into client rendering:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=none,caption={The route tree.}]
app/
  layout.tsx              # root: fonts, ThemeProvider, global CSS
  globals.css             # design tokens + Tailwind v4 wiring
  page.tsx                # public landing (Nav, Hero, TerminalDemo, Features, Footer)
  login/page.tsx          # auth + two-step onboarding
  (app)/                  # route GROUP - the authenticated shell
    layout.tsx            # sidebar + auth gate + keyboard shortcuts + ToastProvider
    chat/page.tsx         # the chat centerpiece (SSE streaming)
    conversations/page.tsx
    documents/page.tsx
    documents/[docId]/page.tsx   # per-document view + intelligence
    meeting/page.tsx
    admin/page.tsx
\end{lstlisting}

The \code{(app)} parentheses make a \textbf{route group}: it wraps every authenticated page in a
shared layout (sidebar, auth gate, keyboard shortcuts, toasts) \emph{without} adding an \code{/app}
URL segment---so chat is at \code{/chat}. Two Next-15 specifics appear in the code:
\code{useSearchParams()} (reading \code{?session=}/\code{?doc=}) is wrapped in a \code{<Suspense>}
boundary, and theming uses \code{next-themes} with \code{attribute="class"} toggling \code{.dark} on
\code{<html>}.

\section{The Design System --- Ink, Paper, Amber}
The visual design is governed by \code{DESIGN.md} and implemented precisely. The brand voice is
\emph{``a calm library with an engine room underneath''}, expressed through three typefaces---%
\textbf{Fraunces} (serif, the ``wisdom'' voice: headlines, wordmark), \textbf{Inter} (sans, body/UI,
weights 400/500 only), \textbf{JetBrains Mono} (the ``machinery'' voice: terminal, trace lines,
labels)---and a tightly constrained palette (Figure~\ref{fig:palette}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[x=1mm,y=1mm, every node/.style={font=\scriptsize}]
\begin{scope}
\definecolor{c0}{HTML}{F5F1E8}\definecolor{c1}{HTML}{FDFBF5}\definecolor{c2}{HTML}{2C2820}\definecolor{c3}{HTML}{E7E0CF}
\fill[c0,draw=ink] (0,0) rectangle (22,12); \node at (11,-3) {bg-main};
\fill[c1,draw=ink] (26,0) rectangle (48,12); \node at (37,-3) {bg-card};
\fill[c2,draw=ink] (52,0) rectangle (74,12); \node[white] at (63,6) {text}; \node at (63,-3) {primary};
\fill[c3,draw=ink] (78,0) rectangle (100,12); \node at (89,-3) {border};
\end{scope}
\node[font=\scriptsize\itshape] at (50,18) {Theme-dependent (light ``paper'' shown)};
% constants row
\begin{scope}[yshift=-30mm]
\definecolor{k0}{HTML}{211E19}\definecolor{k1}{HTML}{1F1C17}\definecolor{k2}{HTML}{E8C87E}\definecolor{k3}{HTML}{F5F1E8}
\fill[k0,draw=ink] (0,0) rectangle (22,12); \node[white] at (11,6) {ink}; \node at (11,-3) {sidebar};
\fill[k1,draw=ink] (26,0) rectangle (48,12); \node[white] at (37,6) {terminal}; \node at (37,-3) {surfaces};
\fill[k2,draw=ink] (52,0) rectangle (74,12); \node at (63,6) {accent}; \node at (63,-3) {amber};
\fill[k3,draw=ink] (78,0) rectangle (100,12); \node at (89,-3) {paper};
\node[font=\scriptsize\itshape] at (50,18) {Constants --- identical in both modes};
\end{scope}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{The ink--paper--amber palette. Theme-dependent tokens flip between light/dark; the constants
(ink sidebar, terminal surfaces, amber accent, paper) never change. Amber \code{\#E8C87E} is the
\emph{only} accent color---no purple, gradients, glassmorphism, or drop shadows.}
\label{fig:palette}
\end{figure}

Every color is a CSS variable wired into Tailwind v4 via \code{@theme inline}, so a utility like
\code{bg-main} emits \code{var(--bg-main)} and re-resolves when the theme flips; components reference
tokens, never hex. \textbf{The signature trace line.} Under every \emph{grounded} answer,
\code{ChatMessage.tsx} renders a JetBrains-Mono microline \code{hybrid -> rrf -> rerank(5) $\cdot$
287ms}, surfacing the real retrieval pipeline and measured latency---making the ``engine room''
visible.

\section{The API Layer \& SWR Caching}
\code{lib/api.ts} is the single place every backend call lives, centralizing three cross-cutting
concerns: \textbf{bearer-token injection} (from \code{localStorage}), \textbf{uniform error handling}
(a typed \code{ApiError} carrying status + backend detail), and \textbf{401 auto-logout}. Token
handling is \emph{display-only} on the client---\code{lib/auth.ts} decodes (but never verifies) the
JWT payload to render name/role/department; the backend verifies the signature on every request.

\textbf{The SSE exception.} Chat cannot use the native \code{EventSource} (it only does
unauthenticated GETs), so \code{queryChat()} reads the SSE stream off \code{fetch}'s
\code{ReadableStream} by hand---splitting on the \code{\textbackslash n\textbackslash n} delimiter,
dispatching each \code{data:} frame, and recognizing \code{[DONE]}/\code{[ERROR]}. It returns an
\code{AbortController} so an in-flight answer can be cancelled.

\textbf{SWR for cache-first reads} (\code{lib/hooks.ts}), Table~\ref{tab:swr}:

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{SWR read hooks and their revalidation policies.}
\label{tab:swr}
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{l l X}
\toprule
\textbf{Hook} & \textbf{Endpoint} & \textbf{Policy}\\
\midrule
\code{useSessions()} & \code{GET /chat/sessions} & Background refresh every 30\,s.\\
\code{useDocuments()} & \code{GET /documents} & \textbf{Adaptive}: 5\,s while any doc is \code{processing}, else 30\,s; raises a toast on \code{processing}$\to$\code{ready}/\code{failed}.\\
\code{useDepartments()} & \code{GET /departments} & No focus/reconnect revalidation.\\
\code{useMe()} & \code{GET /auth/me} & Once, cached for the session.\\
\code{useAnalyticsOverview()} & \code{GET /analytics/overview} & Every 60\,s.\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

The adaptive document polling tightens the loop only while something is in flight and surfaces
completion as a toast even to a user who navigated to the chat page.

\section{Key Screens \& Their Data Flows}
\textbf{The application shell} (\code{(app)/layout.tsx}) is a resizable, collapsible \textbf{ink
sidebar} on every authenticated page: wordmark, search (\code{Cmd+K}), primary nav (Chat,
Conversations, Documents, Upload, Meeting, and---admins only---Admin), the last 8 chat sessions, a
``new chat'' button, and a user pill (avatar initial, name, role badge, department). It owns the
\textbf{auth gate} (redirect to \code{/login} if not logged in), persists collapse/width state to
\code{localStorage}, and registers \textbf{global keyboard shortcuts} (\code{Cmd+K} focus search,
\code{Cmd+N} new chat, \code{Cmd+/} help, \code{Esc} close). Role gating is visual here (the Admin
link shows only for admins), with real enforcement on the server.

\textbf{Login \& onboarding} (\code{login/page.tsx}) implements the two-step flow of
Section~\ref{sec:auth} as one screen with a \code{mode} (sign in/up) and a \code{step} (credentials /
department), saving a fresh token before navigating.

\textbf{Chat} (\code{(app)/chat/page.tsx}), the centerpiece, is a streaming conversation view
(Figure~\ref{fig:chatseq}). On send it optimistically appends the user bubble and an empty streaming
assistant bubble, calls \code{queryChat()}, accumulates tokens live via \code{onToken}, stamps the
wall-clock latency on \code{onDone}, and \code{finalize()} re-fetches the persisted message to attach
the server-resolved citation sources. It reads \code{?session=} to load a conversation and \code{?doc=}
to \textbf{scope} retrieval to one document (the backend's \code{document\_id} narrowing). Answers
render through \code{ChatMessage.tsx}, which strips \code{[Source: N]} into amber citation chips,
renders Markdown (\code{react-markdown} + \code{remark-gfm}), and shows a \code{filename $\cdot$ p.N}
source row plus the trace line.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=5mm and 10mm]
\node[box,minimum width=44mm] (s1) {User types + sends};
\node[box, below=of s1, minimum width=44mm] (s2) {append user bubble + empty streaming bubble};
\node[box, below=of s2, minimum width=44mm] (s3) {queryChat(text, sessionId, handlers, docId)};
\node[box, below=of s3, minimum width=44mm] (s4) {POST /chat/query (SSE)};
\node[box, below=of s4, minimum width=44mm] (s5) {onToken $\to$ append to bubble (loop)};
\node[box, below=of s5, minimum width=44mm] (s6) {[DONE] $\to$ onDone stamps traceMs};
\node[accentbox, below=of s6, minimum width=44mm] (s7) {finalize(): GET messages $\to$ attach sources};
\draw[arr](s1)--(s2);\draw[arr](s2)--(s3);\draw[arr](s3)--(s4);\draw[arr](s4)--(s5);\draw[arr](s5)--(s6);\draw[arr](s6)--(s7);
\draw[darr] (s5.east) to[bend left=60] node[lbl,right]{repeat per token} (s4.east);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{The chat streaming data flow: optimistic bubbles, live token accumulation, latency stamping,
then a finalize re-fetch to attach server-resolved citations.}
\label{fig:chatseq}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Other screens.} \textbf{Documents} list/upload (with adaptive polling and ready/failed toasts)
plus a per-document detail page that triggers and displays intelligence (Section~\ref{sec:intel}).
\textbf{Conversations} lists and deletes sessions. \textbf{Meeting} provides the paste-or-upload
transcript analyzer. \textbf{Admin} renders the six analytics endpoints (via Recharts) and the
user/department management tables. The public \textbf{landing page} is composed of Nav, Hero, the
typing TerminalDemo, the feature band, and Footer. \code{lib/exportChat.ts} exports a conversation to
PDF via the browser print path, and \code{lib/useToast.ts} powers the document-status toasts.

%==============================================================================
\chapter{Evaluation \& Research}
\label{ch:eval}
%==============================================================================

Pragya's research contribution is a controlled comparison of the three retrieval configurations over
one fixed corpus and thirty ground-truth questions, scored with RAGAS. The harness is in
\code{backend/evaluation/}; the committed results are in \code{final\_results.json}. This chapter
reports the methodology and the real numbers in full, including the results that did \emph{not} match
the intuitive hypothesis.

\section{RAGAS Methodology}
The harness separates \textbf{generation} (expensive, rate-limited) from \textbf{scoring} (must be
re-runnable) (Figure~\ref{fig:evalphases}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=7mm and 14mm]
\node[group, label={[lbl]above:Phase 1 --- Generation (Gemini)}] (p1box) {%
  \begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=5mm]
  \node[box,minimum width=40mm] (g1) {30 questions $\times$ 3 methods:\\\scriptsize retrieve $\to$ prompt $\to$ Gemini answer};
  \node[box, below=of g1, minimum width=40mm] (g2) {write results\_<method>.json\\\scriptsize after EVERY question (resumable)};
  \draw[arr] (g1)--(g2);
  \end{tikzpicture}};
\node[box, below left=14mm and -10mm of p1box, minimum width=34mm] (cp) {context\_precision@3\\\scriptsize Groq llama-3.1-8b};
\node[box, below right=14mm and -10mm of p1box, minimum width=34mm] (fa) {faithfulness@2\\\scriptsize local Ollama qwen2.5:7b};
\node[accentbox, below=42mm of p1box, minimum width=40mm] (agg) {mean per method $\to$ table\\$\to$ final\_results.json};
\draw[arr] (p1box.south) -- (cp.north);
\draw[arr] (p1box.south) -- (fa.north);
\draw[arr] (cp.south) -- (agg.north);
\draw[arr] (fa.south) -- (agg.north);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Decoupled evaluation: generation writes to disk after every question (resumable on a
free-tier 429); scoring reads from disk with two independent judges.}
\label{fig:evalphases}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Phase 1} retrieves with the given method, builds the \emph{exact same} citation prompt the live
app uses (reusing \code{build\_citation\_prompt} and \code{\_dedupe\_by\_parent}, so scored contexts are
byte-for-byte what the model saw), and asks Gemini for a grounded answer, writing results after every
question (a 429 never re-burns answers). Generation is paced (4\,s between calls, 15\,s every 10
questions, 30\,s between experiments). The test corpus is auto-selected as the department owning the
most documents (the Infovance corpus), queried by a mock admin user so the visibility filter admits it.

\textbf{The two metrics, and why only these.} \code{context\_precision@3} (kept --- most directly
measures retrieval quality, one context per judge call fits the token budget); \code{faithfulness@2}
(kept, but moved off Groq, Section~\ref{sec:judges}); \code{answer\_relevancy} (excluded --- needs a
real embedding model the Groq judge lacks, and mostly reflects generation, which is held constant
across methods).

\textbf{The K-normalization.} Since the methods return different context counts (dense $\approx 8$
deduped parents, hybrid $\approx 12$, rerank 5), scoring caps to a fixed top-3 (context precision) and
top-2 (faithfulness), making the comparison a clean precision@$K$. The cited block is always
\code{[Source: 1]}, so the relevant context is never capped out.

\section{The 30-Question Benchmark Set}
The benchmark (\code{test\_questions.py}) is 30 ground-truth Q/A pairs authored directly from the six
core Infovance documents---every question answerable from the text (RAGAS metrics are only meaningful
when the ground truth is present in the searched corpus). Figure~\ref{fig:cats} shows the category
distribution.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  xbar, width=11cm, height=5.6cm, bar width=10pt, xmin=0, xmax=6,
  symbolic y coords={cross-document, onboarding, engineering, finance, helpdesk, security, hr},
  ytick=data, nodes near coords, nodes near coords style={font=\scriptsize},
  xlabel={\# questions}, enlarge y limits=0.12, xmajorgrids, tick label style={font=\small},
]
\addplot[fill=amber, draw=amberdark] coordinates {
  (5,hr) (4,security) (4,helpdesk) (5,finance) (4,engineering) (4,onboarding) (4,cross-document)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Benchmark composition: 30 questions across seven categories ($\geq 4$ per source document).
The \emph{cross-document} category pairs facts that each live in only one document, so a correct answer
requires retrieving from two documents at once.}
\label{fig:cats}
\end{figure}

\begin{divergence}
\code{CLAUDE.md} describes ``50 fixed test questions.'' The implemented and committed benchmark contains
\textbf{30}. This report uses the real number throughout. Thirty questions across seven categories is a
defensible size for a single-corpus comparison; the gap from the planned 50 is noted honestly.
\end{divergence}

Representative questions (verbatim): \emph{Q1 (hr)} ``How many casual leaves are employees entitled to
per year?'' ($\to$ 12 days, lapses); \emph{Q6 (security)} ``minimum password length and rotation?''
($\to$ 12 chars, every 90 days); \emph{Q15 (finance)} ``approving authority above INR 50,000?'' ($\to$
the CFO); \emph{Q27 (cross-document)} combines the Security Policy (five failed attempts) and the
Helpdesk SOP (a P2 ticket).

\section{The Two-Independent-Judge Design}
\label{sec:judges}
The central safeguard: \textbf{no model grades its own output}. Three different models span generation
and scoring (Table~\ref{tab:judges}).

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{The three models---generator plus two independent judges.}
\label{tab:judges}
\begin{tabularx}{\linewidth}{l l X}
\toprule
\textbf{Role} & \textbf{Model} & \textbf{Why}\\
\midrule
Generator & Gemini \code{gemini-3.1-flash-lite} & The system's real chat model; fast, free-tier.\\
Context-precision judge & Groq \code{llama-3.1-8b-instant} & Independent; one context per call fits the budget.\\
Faithfulness judge & \emph{local} Ollama \code{qwen2.5:7b} & Independent; runs locally, no rate limit.\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

\textbf{Why faithfulness moved to a local model.} Faithfulness packs all contexts into a single
$\sim$6--12k-token NLI call; the Groq free tier caps a request at 6000 tokens/minute (HTTP 413), and
\code{llama-3.1-8b} could not reliably emit the parseable JSON its statement-extraction needs---both
confirmed empirically. The fix was a local \code{qwen2.5:7b} (no token limit, clean JSON), still
independent of the generator. Even this needed care: Ollama defaults to a $\sim$4k window, which a
top-2 prompt of two $\sim$2k-token parents overflows into a runaway generation; the harness sets
\code{num\_ctx = 8192}, caps \code{num\_predict = 2048}, and adds a hard 300\,s per-question timeout.

\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}
The headline comparison from \code{final\_results.json} (means over 30 questions; context precision is
precision@3 by Groq, faithfulness is @2 by local qwen2.5):

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{RAGAS comparison of the three retrieval methods.}
\label{tab:results}
\begin{tabular}{l c c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Method} & \textbf{Faithfulness} & \textbf{Context Precision} & \textbf{Average} & \textbf{Cells scored}\\
\midrule
Dense (A) & 0.873 & 0.936 & \textbf{0.905} & 30 / 30\\
Hybrid (B) & 0.886 & 0.928 & \textbf{0.907} & 29 / 30\\
Hybrid + Rerank (C) & 0.750 & 0.900 & \textbf{0.825} & 30 / 30\\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  ybar, width=12.5cm, height=6.2cm, bar width=15pt,
  ymin=0.70, ymax=0.97, ylabel={Score (higher is better)},
  symbolic x coords={A,B,C}, xtick=data,
  xticklabels={Dense (A), Hybrid (B), Hybrid+Rerank (C)},
  nodes near coords, nodes near coords style={font=\scriptsize, /pgf/number format/fixed, /pgf/number format/precision=3},
  enlarge x limits=0.25, ymajorgrids, legend pos=south west,
  legend style={font=\small}, tick label style={font=\small},
]
\addplot[fill=ink, draw=ink] coordinates {(A,0.873)(B,0.886)(C,0.750)};
\addplot[fill=amber, draw=amberdark] coordinates {(A,0.936)(B,0.928)(C,0.900)};
\legend{Faithfulness, Context precision}
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{RAGAS scores by retrieval method. Context precision (amber) is high and similar across all
three; faithfulness (ink) collapses for hybrid+rerank---the headline negative result.}
\label{fig:results}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=12.5cm, height=4.6cm, ybar, bar width=22pt,
  ymin=0.80, ymax=0.92, ylabel={Average score},
  symbolic x coords={A,B,C}, xtick=data,
  xticklabels={Dense (A), Hybrid (B), Hybrid+Rerank (C)},
  nodes near coords, nodes near coords style={font=\small, /pgf/number format/fixed, /pgf/number format/precision=3},
  enlarge x limits=0.3, ymajorgrids, tick label style={font=\small},
]
\addplot[fill=amber, draw=amberdark] coordinates {(A,0.905)(B,0.907)(C,0.825)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Average of the two metrics. Hybrid (B) edges out dense (A) by only $0.002$; hybrid+rerank (C)
is clearly worst. The A--B near-tie is consistent with the non-functional sparse channel
(Section~\ref{sec:sparse}).}
\label{fig:avg}
\end{figure}

The A$\to$C change per metric: faithfulness \textbf{$-0.123$} ($0.873 \to 0.750$) and context precision
\textbf{$-0.036$} ($0.936 \to 0.900$). Adding the full reranking stage moved \emph{both} metrics in the
wrong direction on this corpus.

\section{Honest Findings \& Limitations}
\label{sec:findings}
\paragraph{Finding 1 --- Hybrid is best, but only barely; dense is essentially tied.} Hybrid (B) takes
the top average ($0.907$) over dense ($0.905$)---a difference of $0.002$, within noise. On this corpus,
adding the sparse channel barely changed anything, exactly as Section~\ref{sec:sparse} predicts: the
sparse vectors do not align between ingestion and query, so ``hybrid'' is effectively dense fused with a
near-empty list. A working sparse channel is the single change most likely to separate B from A.

\paragraph{Finding 2 --- Reranking \emph{degraded} quality, via over-pruning.} The most elaborate
pipeline (C) scored \emph{lowest}, and the damage is concentrated in faithfulness ($0.87$--$0.89 \to
0.75$). The plausible mechanism is over-pruning: cutting to a top-5 of parents sometimes drops a context
block the answer needed, and an answer missing a supporting source is judged less faithful. On a small,
clean, single-domain corpus where dense retrieval is already precise, the cross-encoder's pruning
removes more signal than its reranking adds. \textbf{More pipeline is not automatically better}---and it
took a real evaluation to show it.

\paragraph{Finding 3 --- The differences are small because the corpus is easy.} All three methods score
$0.90+$ on context precision and $\geq 0.75$ on faithfulness. Six well-structured policy documents with
distinct vocabularies are a relatively easy retrieval target; the methods would likely separate more on
a larger, noisier, more overlapping corpus.

\paragraph{Limitations, stated plainly.}
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{The sparse channel is non-functional} (Section~\ref{sec:sparse}), so ``hybrid'' here is
  not a fully realized hybrid; read the B-vs-A comparison with that caveat.
  \item \textbf{One faithfulness cell is missing for hybrid} (29/30 scored---one question timed out on
  the local 7B and was recorded as NaN, then excluded), so hybrid's faithfulness is a mean over 29.
  \item \textbf{The K-asymmetry} is controlled by capping to precision@3 / faithfulness@2, a
  normalization rather than a perfect equalization.
  \item \textbf{Judges are 7--8B models}---independent of the generator (the key property) but smaller
  than a frontier judge; absolute scores would shift, though the relative ordering is the load-bearing
  result.
  \item \textbf{Single corpus, single run} (30 questions, one pass): the findings are directional, not
  statistically powered.
\end{itemize}

\begin{observation}
Despite the limitations, the study does what many RAG write-ups do not: a genuine controlled comparison
with bias-controlled judges, reporting a \textbf{negative result honestly}---that the reranker hurt on
this corpus and the sparse channel added nothing. For an internship project aimed at a research venue,
the discipline to find and report those results is as valuable as a clean win would have been.
\end{observation}

