%==============================================================================
\chapter{Synthesis \& Conclusions}
\label{ch:synthesis}
%==============================================================================

This chapter draws together the report's threads into a set of observations and conclusions derived
from the system and its data---the author's own analysis rather than a restatement of the code.

\section{The Architecture's Central Bet Paid Off}
Pragya's defining structural decision---enforcing access control \emph{inside} the vector-database
query rather than in application logic---is validated by how cleanly the rest of the system composes
around it. Because the visibility filter is a single shared object (Section~\ref{sec:visibility}), chat,
document search, and document-scoped retrieval all inherit identical access semantics for free, and the
``personal'' privacy guarantee holds even against admins. The same denormalize-into-the-payload move
that enables this also removes a database round-trip at generation time (parent text travels with the
vector). One decision buys correctness \emph{and} performance---the hallmark of a good architectural
bet.

\section{The Data Tells a Coherent Story}
The three most striking numbers in the evaluation are not independent---they are the same phenomenon
seen three ways. The near-tie between dense ($0.905$) and hybrid ($0.907$), the documented sparse-index
defect (Section~\ref{sec:sparse}), and the small absolute spread of all scores are mutually consistent:
\textbf{a corpus easy enough that dense retrieval alone nearly saturates the metrics leaves little room
for any second signal to matter}---and the second signal (sparse) is, in this build, not actually
present. The evaluation thus measures two things at once: the retrieval methods, and the corpus's
difficulty. A harder corpus is the lever that would make the method differences legible.

\section{Cost Versus Quality --- The Reranker's Verdict}
Plotting the three methods on cost against average quality (Figure~\ref{fig:costquality}) makes the
central engineering lesson visual: the most expensive method is also the worst. Dense and hybrid sit at
the efficient frontier; the reranker pays the most (a forward pass over $\sim$40 pairs) to land lowest.

\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
  width=11.5cm, height=6cm, xlabel={Relative retrieval cost $\to$}, ylabel={Average RAGAS score},
  xmin=0.5, xmax=3.5, ymin=0.80, ymax=0.93, xtick={1,2,3},
  xticklabels={dense\\(1 search), hybrid\\(2 searches), hybrid+rerank\\(+$\sim$40 cross-enc.)},
  xticklabel style={align=center, font=\scriptsize}, ymajorgrids, tick label style={font=\small},
]
\addplot[only marks, mark=*, mark size=3.2pt, color=amberdark] coordinates {(1,0.905)(2,0.907)(3,0.825)};
\node[anchor=south, font=\scriptsize] at (axis cs:1,0.905) {Dense 0.905};
\node[anchor=south, font=\scriptsize] at (axis cs:2,0.907) {Hybrid 0.907};
\node[anchor=north, font=\scriptsize] at (axis cs:3,0.825) {Rerank 0.825};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Cost versus quality. On this corpus, increasing pipeline cost did not increase quality; the
cheapest two methods are the best, and the most expensive is the worst---a concrete instance of
``more pipeline is not automatically better.''}
\label{fig:costquality}
\end{figure}

\section{What This Project Demonstrates}
Three things stand out as the project's real contributions. \textbf{Engineering breadth}: a working
full-stack system spanning async Python, two databases, an LLM integration with streaming, a learned
reranker, and a modern React frontend---each built to a stated standard and committed incrementally.
\textbf{Engineering honesty}: a known defect (the sparse channel) documented and quantified rather than
hidden, and a negative research result (the reranker hurt) reported rather than buried. \textbf{Research
discipline}: a controlled comparison with bias-controlled judges that produces a defensible, if
modest, finding. For an internship aimed at both an industry deliverable and graduate study, this
combination---a real system, measured rigorously, reported truthfully---is the strongest possible
outcome.

