\chapter{Glossary}
\label{app:glossary}
\begin{description}
  \item[RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation)] Answering with an LLM whose input is augmented by
  passages retrieved from a corpus, grounding answers in real sources.
  \item[Embedding] A fixed-length vector representing the meaning of text, so similar meanings are
  nearby.
  \item[Dense vector / retrieval] Retrieval by embedding similarity (meaning-based); Pragya uses 768-d
  Gemini embeddings compared by cosine.
  \item[Sparse vector / BM25] Retrieval by keyword overlap; mostly zeros, with non-zero entries at
  hashed word indices weighted by term frequency.
  \item[Hybrid retrieval] Combining dense and sparse to capture both meaning and exact keywords.
  \item[RRF (Reciprocal Rank Fusion)] A parameter-free merge of two ranked lists by summing
  $1/(k+\text{rank})$ ($k=60$); rewards items ranked well by both retrievers.
  \item[Bi-encoder] Encodes query and document independently, then compares vectors (cheap).
  \item[Cross-encoder] Feeds the (query, document) pair through a transformer together for a joint
  relevance score (accurate, costly).
  \item[Reranking] Re-scoring a small candidate set with a cross-encoder and keeping the best few.
  \item[Hierarchical chunking] Small \emph{child} chunks (precise retrieval) nested in larger
  \emph{parent} chunks (richer generation context); retrieve on children, generate from parents.
  \item[Matryoshka embedding] An embedding whose any prefix is itself valid, allowing truncation
  (3072$\to$768) with minimal quality loss.
  \item[Asymmetric embedding] Embedding queries and documents with different task-type hints so they
  map into a shared space.
  \item[Qdrant] The vector database storing dense + sparse vectors and access-control payload.
  \item[SSE (Server-Sent Events)] A one-way HTTP streaming format (\code{data: ...}) used to stream
  answer tokens.
  \item[JWT (JSON Web Token)] A signed, stateless token carrying user id, department, and role.
  \item[RBAC (Role-Based Access Control)] Restricting actions by role and, here, retrieval by
  department/visibility tier.
  \item[Hallucination] An LLM producing confident but unsupported content; guarded by constraining the
  model to retrieved context.
  \item[RAGAS] A framework of LLM-as-judge metrics for evaluating RAG systems.
  \item[Faithfulness] The degree to which an answer's claims are supported by the retrieved contexts.
  \item[Context precision] The degree to which the retrieved contexts are relevant to the ground-truth
  answer.
  \item[NLI (Natural Language Inference)] Judging whether a statement is entailed by a text; the
  mechanism behind faithfulness.
\end{description}

